{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}
{{Use Indian English|date=October 2017}}
'''Aaya Ram Gaya Ram''' expression in politics of [[India]] means frequent floor-crossing by legislatures. The term was coined when [[Gaya Lal]] a [[Member of the Legislative Assembly]] from [[Haryana]] in 1967 changed party thrice in a fortnight first from the [[Indian National Congress]] to United Front, back to Congress and then within nine hours to United Front again. When Gaya Lal decided to quit the United Front and join the Congress, then Congress leader [[Rao Birendra Singh]] brought him to [[Chandigarh]] press and declared "Gaya Ram was now Aya Ram". It became the subject of numerous jokes and cartoons. In 1985 the Constitution amended the anti-defection act. <ref>http://www.hindustantimes.com/india/here-is-all-you-wanted-to-know-about-the-anti-defection-law/story-49d09jR4iSNmKI5w83u2IL.html</ref> to prevent such defections.<ref>http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-12-21/chandigarh/30542163_1_bhajan-lal-bansi-lal-vinod-bhayana</ref> It was included in constitution by Rajiv Gandhi Government as the tenth schedule of Indian constitution.

